│  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boundary_layer Published Time:               │
│  2003-05-10T03:23:25Z Markdown Content: [![Image                            │
│  1](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/Thermal-plum  │
│  e-from-human-hand.jpg/330px-Thermal-plume-from-human-hand.jpg)](https://e  │
│  n.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Thermal-plume-from-human-hand.jpg) The boundary  │
│  layer around a human hand, [schlieren                                      │
│  photograph](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schlieren_photograph "Schlieren  │
│  photograph"). The boundary layer is the bright-green border, most visible  │
│  on the back of the hand (click for high-res image). In                     │
│  [physics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics "Physics") and [fluid      │
│  mechanics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_mechanics "Fluid            │
│  mechanics"), a **boundary layer** is the thin layer of                     │
│  [fluid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid "Fluid") in the immediate      │
│  vicinity of a [bounding                                                    │
│  surface](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boundary_(thermodynamic) "Boundary  │
│  (thermodynamic)") formed by the fluid flowing along the surface. The       │
│  fluid's interaction with the wall induces a                                │
│  [no-slip](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No-slip_condition "No-slip         │
│  condition") boundary condition (zero velocity at the wall). The [flow      │
│  velocity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flow_velocity "Flow velocity")     │
│  then monotonically increases above the surface until it returns to the     │
│  bulk flow velocity. The thin layer consisting of fluid whose velocity has  │
│  not yet returned to the bulk flow velocity is called the velocity bo       │
│                                                                             │
