│  line from the leading edge to the trailing edge) and the direction of the  │
│  oncoming air. Increasing the angle of attack (up to a certain point)       │
│  increases the lift, as it causes the wing to deflect more air downwards    │
│  and enhances the pressure differential. However, if the angle becomes too  │
│  steep, the airflow can separate from the wing, leading to a loss of lift,  │
│  known as a **stall**.\n*   **Wing Shape / Coefficient of Lift ($C_L$):**   │
│  This factor represents the efficiency of the wing's design. Different      │
│  wing designs (e.g., thin, swept-back wings for speed vs. thick,            │
│  high-camber wings for slower flight) have different inherent lift          │
│  characteristics. Flaps and slats, which are movable parts on the wing,     │
│  can also change the wing's effective shape to increase $C_L$ during        │
