│        "theory_explanation": "To overcome drag and propel an aircraft       │
│  forward, we need **Thrust**. Thrust is the force that moves an aircraft    │
│  through the air. It's the \"push\" or \"pull\" that gets the plane going   │
│  and keeps it moving.\n\n## How Thrust is Generated\n\nThrust is generated  │
│  by an aircraft's propulsion system, primarily through the powerful         │
│  application of **Newton's Third Law of Motion**.\n\n*   **The Core         │
│  Principle:** Engines work by accelerating a mass of air or hot gas in one  │
│  direction. According to Newton's Third Law, for every action, there is an  │
│  equal and opposite reaction.\n*   **Action:** The engine forcefully        │
│  expels air or gas backward.\n*   **Reaction:** This expulsion creates an   │
│  equal and opposite forward force on the engine itself, which is the        │
│  **Thrust** that pushes the aircraft forward.\n\nLet's look at the two      │
│  main types of engines:\n\n1.  **Propeller Engines:**\n    *                │
│  **Mechanism:** A propeller is essentially a rotating wing. Its blades are  │
│  shaped like airfoils.\n    *   **How it works:** As the propeller spins,   │
│  its blades cut through the air, creating a pressure difference. The front  │
│  side of the blade creates lower pressure, and the back side creates        │
│  higher pressure. This pushes a large volume of air backward.\n    *        │
│  **Thrust Generation:** By pushing air backward, the propeller creates a    │
│  forward pulling (or pushing) force on the aircraft.\n\n2.  **Jet           │
│  Engines:**\n    *   **Mechanism:** Jet engines operate on a more complex   │
│  cycle of intake, compression, combustion, and exhaust.\n    *   **How it   │
│  works:**\n        *   **Intake:** Air is sucked into the front of the      │
│  engine.\n        *   **Compression:** A series of rotating blades          │
│  (compressors) squeeze and compress this air, increasing its pressure and   │
│  temperature.\n        *   **Combustion:** Fuel is injected into the        │
│  compressed air and ignited, creating a massive expansion of hot,           │
│  high-pressure gases.\n        *   **Exhaust:** These hot gases are then    │
│  forced out through a nozzle at very high speed, often passing through a    │
│  turbine that drives the compressor.\n    *   **Thrust Generation:** The    │
│  high-velocity expulsion of hot gases backward generates a powerful         │
│  forward thrust on the engine and aircraft.\n\nIn essence, whether it's a   │
│  propeller \"throwing\" air backward or a jet engine \"shooting\" hot       │
│  gases backward, the principle remains the same: push something backward,   │
│  and you get pushed forward.",                                              │
