│        "theory_explanation": "While lift and thrust work to get an          │
│  aircraft into the air and move it forward, **Weight** is the force         │
│  constantly trying to pull it back down.\n\n## Gravity's Role\n\n*          │
│  **Definition:** Weight is the force exerted by gravity on an object's      │
│  mass. For an aircraft, it's the total gravitational pull on the entire     │
│  machine, including its structure, engines, fuel, passengers, and           │
│  cargo.\n*   **Direction:** Weight always acts vertically downwards,        │
│  towards the center of the Earth.\n*   **Magnitude:** The magnitude of the  │
│  weight force depends directly on the aircraft's mass. A heavier aircraft   │
│  (more fuel, more passengers) will have greater weight.\n*                  │
│  **Counteracting Weight:** To achieve level flight, the lift generated by   │
│  the wings must be equal to the aircraft's total weight. If lift is         │
│  greater than weight, the aircraft climbs; if lift is less than weight, it  │
│  descends.\n\nUnderstanding weight is crucial for pilots and engineers.     │
│  Pilots must manage fuel consumption and passenger/cargo loads to ensure    │
│  the aircraft remains within its safe weight limits for takeoff, flight,    │
│  and landing. Engineers design the aircraft structure to withstand the      │
│  stresses associated with its maximum operating weight.",                   │
