│        "topic_title": "Equilibrium of Forces",                              │
│        "theory_explanation": "For an aircraft to fly in a stable,           │
│  unaccelerated manner (like cruising at a constant altitude and speed),     │
│  the four fundamental forces acting upon it must be in **equilibrium**,     │
│  meaning they are perfectly balanced.\n\n## The Four Forces\n\nRecall the   │
│  four forces of flight:\n\n1.  **Lift:** Acts upwards, opposing             │
│  weight.\n2.  **Weight:** Acts downwards, due to gravity.\n3.  **Thrust:**  │
│  Acts forwards, propelling the aircraft.\n4.  **Drag:** Acts backwards,     │
│  opposing thrust.\n\n## Achieving Equilibrium\n\nWhen an aircraft is in     │
│  equilibrium, it means:\n\n*   **Vertical Equilibrium:** The upward force   │
│  of **Lift** is equal to the downward force of **Weight**.\n    $$Lift =    │
│  Weight$$\n    *   If $Lift > Weight$, the aircraft will climb.\n    *      │
│  If $Lift < Weight$, the aircraft will descend.\n\n*   **Horizontal         │
│  Equilibrium:** The forward force of **Thrust** is equal to the backward    │
│  force of **Drag**.\n    $$Thrust = Drag$$\n    *   If $Thrust > Drag$,     │
│  the aircraft will accelerate.\n    *   If $Thrust < Drag$, the aircraft    │
│  will decelerate.\n\n## The Dance of Balance\n\nThink of it as a delicate   │
│  dance. When a pilot wants to climb, they might increase thrust (which      │
│  increases airspeed, and therefore lift) or increase the angle of attack,   │
│  temporarily making lift greater than weight. When they want to slow down,  │
│  they might reduce thrust, allowing drag to momentarily overcome            │
│  thrust.\n\nFor most of a flight, especially during cruise, the goal is to  │
│  maintain this equilibrium to ensure a smooth, stable journey.              │
│  Understanding equilibrium is fundamental to understanding how an aircraft  │
│  performs various maneuvers.",                                              │
