│        "topic_title": "Continuity equation (simplified)",                   │
│        "theory_explanation": "Imagine you're watering your garden with a    │
│  hose. If you put your thumb over part of the opening, what happens to the  │
│  water's speed? It speeds up, right? This simple observation demonstrates   │
│  a fundamental principle in fluid dynamics called the **Continuity          │
│  Equation**.\n\nThe Continuity Equation is essentially a statement of       │
│  **conservation of mass** for a fluid in motion. It tells us that for a     │
│  fluid flowing through a pipe or channel, the amount of fluid (mass)        │
│  entering a section must be equal to the amount of fluid leaving that       │
│  section, assuming no fluid is added or removed along the way.\n\nFor most  │
│  aerospace applications at lower speeds, we can simplify this even further  │
│  by assuming the air is **incompressible** (its density doesn't change      │
│  much). In this case, the *volume* of fluid flowing past any point per      │
│  unit of time must remain constant.\n\nThink of it like a conveyor belt     │
│  carrying packages. If the belt narrows, the packages have to speed up to   │
│  keep the same number of packages passing by per second.\n\n#### The        │
│  Simplified Formula\nFor an incompressible fluid flowing through a pipe or  │
│  channel with varying cross-sectional area, the continuity equation can be  │
│  written as:\n\n$$A_1 V_1 = A_2 V_2$$\n\nWhere:\n*   $A_1$ is the           │
│  cross-sectional area at point 1.\n*   $V_1$ is the average fluid velocity  │
│  at point 1.\n*   $A_2$ is the cross-sectional area at point 2.\n*   $V_2$  │
│  is the average fluid velocity at point 2.\n\nThe product $A \\times V$ is  │
│  called the **volume flow rate** (or discharge), and the continuity         │
│  equation states that this volume flow rate must remain constant.\n\n####   │
│  What it tells us:\n*   **Narrower areas mean faster flow:** If the         │
│  cross-sectional area ($A$) decreases, the fluid velocity ($V$) must        │
│  increase to keep the volume flow rate constant. This is exactly why the    │
│  water speeds up when you constrict the hose opening!\n*   **Wider areas    │
│  mean slower flow:** Conversely, if the area increases, the velocity must   │
│  decrease.\n\nThis principle is crucial for understanding how air speeds    │
│  up over the curved upper surface of an airplane wing, contributing to      │
│  lift, and how it behaves in jet engines and wind tunnels.\n\n**Difficulty  │
│  Rating:** Easy",                                                           │
