│        "topic_title": "Wing planforms (rectangular, tapered, swept)",       │
│        "theory_explanation": "The **wing planform** refers to the shape of  │
│  the wing as viewed from directly above or below. It's not just about       │
│  aesthetics; the planform significantly influences an aircraft's lift       │
│  distribution, drag characteristics, handling, and overall efficiency.      │
│  Aircraft designers choose specific planforms based on the aircraft's       │
│  intended mission.\n\nLet's look at some common types:\n\n*                 │
│  **Rectangular (Regular) Wing**:\n    *   **Description**: This is the      │
│  simplest planform, where the wing has a constant chord length from the     │
│  fuselage (root) all the way to the wingtip.\n    *                         │
│  **Characteristics**:\n        *   **Predictable Stall**: A major           │
│  advantage is its predictable stall behavior. Stalls typically begin at     │
│  the wing root (closest to the fuselage), allowing the outer part of the    │
│  wing to continue generating lift. This preserves control authority for     │
│  the ailerons (which are usually located near the wingtips), making it      │
│  easier for the pilot to recover.\n        *   **Simple Construction**:     │
│  Easy and inexpensive to manufacture.\n        *   **Higher Induced         │
│  Drag**: At cruise speeds, rectangular wings tend to have higher induced    │
│  drag (a type of drag related to lift generation) compared to more          │
│  aerodynamically efficient designs.\n    *   **Applications**: Commonly     │
│  found on training aircraft, light recreational planes, and some older      │
│  transport aircraft where simplicity and predictable handling are           │
│  prioritized.\n\n*   **Tapered Wings**:\n    *   **Description**: In a      │
│  tapered wing, the chord length gradually decreases from the wing root to   │
│  the wingtip.\n    *   **Characteristics**:\n        *   **Improved         │
│  Efficiency**: Tapering helps to achieve a more elliptical lift             │
│  distribution across the wing, which reduces induced drag and improves      │
│  aerodynamic efficiency, especially at higher speeds.\n        *            │
│  **Lighter Structure**: Can be lighter than a rectangular wing for the      │
│  same span.\n        *   **More Complex Stall**: Stall characteristics can  │
│  be less predictable than rectangular wings, sometimes starting at the      │
│  wingtips, which can reduce aileron effectiveness.\n    *                   │
│  **Applications**: Most modern commercial airliners, many military          │
│  aircraft, and high-performance general aviation aircraft.\n\n*   **Swept   │
│  Wings (Sweepback Wings)**:\n    *   **Description**: These wings are       │
│  angled backward from the fuselage.\n    *   **Characteristics**:\n         │
│  *   **High-Speed Performance**: The primary advantage of swept wings is    │
│  their ability to delay the onset of compressibility effects (like          │
│  shockwaves) at high speeds, allowing aircraft to fly faster without        │
│  experiencing a sudden increase in drag.\n        *   **Stability**: Can    │
│  provide better directional stability.\n        *   **Structural            │
│  Complexity**: More complex to design and manufacture than straight         │
│  wings.\n        *   **Stall Characteristics**: Can have less desirable     │
│  stall characteristics, with stalls sometimes starting at the wingtips.\n   │
│  *   **Applications**: Almost all modern jet aircraft (commercial           │
│  airliners, fighter jets) designed for high-speed                           │
│  flight.\n\n**Difficulty:** Medium",                                        │
