│        "topic_title": "Airfoil nomenclature (chord, leading edge, trailing  │
│  edge, camber)",                                                            │
│        "theory_explanation": "Imagine slicing through an airplane wing –    │
│  the shape you see is called an **airfoil**. This special shape is the      │
│  aerodynamic powerhouse, designed to interact with the air to create lift.  │
│  To understand how it works, we need to learn its key parts:\n\n*           │
│  **Leading Edge (LE)**: This is the very front of the airfoil, the part     │
│  that first meets the oncoming air. Think of it as the \"nose\" of the      │
│  wing.\n*   **Trailing Edge (TE)**: This is the very back of the airfoil,   │
│  where the airflow that has traveled over the top and bottom surfaces       │
│  rejoins. It's the \"tail\" of the wing.\n*   **Chord Line**: Picture a     │
│  straight line drawn from the leading edge directly to the trailing edge.   │
│  This imaginary line is the **chord line**. It's a crucial reference for    │
│  many aerodynamic calculations.\n*   **Chord Length ($c$)**: The actual     │
│  distance along the chord line, from the leading edge to the trailing       │
│  edge, is called the **chord length**. It tells us how \"wide\" the         │
│  airfoil is.\n*   **Camber Line**: Now, imagine a curved line that runs     │
│  exactly halfway between the upper and lower surfaces of the airfoil. This  │
│  is the **camber line**, and it represents the mean (average) shape of the  │
│  airfoil.\n*   **Camber**: The maximum distance between the chord line and  │
│  the camber line is simply called **camber**. This curvature is incredibly  │
│  important because it's a primary factor in how much lift an airfoil can    │
│  generate. A more curved (higher camber) airfoil generally produces more    │
│  lift at a given speed.\n\n**Difficulty:** Easy",                           │
