│      {                                                                      │
│        "topic_title": "Angle of Attack (AoA)",                              │
│        "theory_explanation": "The **Angle of Attack (AoA)** is one of the   │
│  most fundamental and critical concepts in aerodynamics. It's the primary   │
│  way a pilot controls the amount of lift an aircraft wing                   │
│  generates.\n\nSimply put, the **Angle of Attack** is the angle between     │
│  the wing's **chord line** (that imaginary line from leading to trailing    │
│  edge) and the **relative wind**. The relative wind is the direction of     │
│  the air flowing over the wing.\n\nThink of it this way:\n*   If you hold   │
│  your hand flat out of a car window, and it's perfectly parallel to the     │
│  ground, your AoA is zero.\n*   If you tilt your hand slightly upwards,     │
│  you're increasing its AoA, and you'll feel it push up (generate            │
│  lift).\n\n**Why is AoA so important?**\n*   **Direct Control of Lift**: A  │
│  small increase in AoA significantly increases the amount of lift produced  │
│  by the wing.\n*   **Independent of Pitch**: It's crucial to understand     │
│  that AoA is *not* the same as the aircraft's pitch attitude (whether the   │
│  nose is pointing up or down). An aircraft can be flying level (zero        │
│  pitch) but have a positive AoA if it's climbing, or it can be descending   │
│  with its nose up if it has a high AoA. It's all about the relationship     │
│  between the wing and the *oncoming air*.\n\nPilots constantly manage the   │
│  AoA to achieve desired flight performance, making it a cornerstone of      │
│  safe and efficient flight.\n\n**Difficulty:** Easy",                       │
