│      {                                                                      │
│        "topic_title": "Stall phenomenon",                                   │
│        "theory_explanation": "The **stall phenomenon** is a critical        │
│  concept for every pilot and aviation enthusiast to understand. It's often  │
│  misunderstood as the engine \"stalling\" or stopping, but in               │
│  aerodynamics, a stall refers to the wing's inability to produce            │
│  sufficient lift.\n\nA stall occurs when the wing reaches its **critical    │
│  angle of attack**. This is a specific angle where, if you increase the     │
│  AoA any further, the wing will *not* produce more lift; instead, it will   │
│  experience a sudden and dramatic loss of lift.\n\n**What happens during a  │
│  stall?**\n1.  **Increased AoA**: As the pilot increases the angle of       │
│  attack, the airflow over the wing's upper surface becomes more             │
│  turbulent.\n2.  **Critical Angle Reached**: At the critical angle of       │
│  attack, the smooth, laminar airflow that normally hugs the upper surface   │
│  of the wing can no longer do so. It \"separates\" from the wing.\n3.       │
│  **Loss of Lift**: This airflow separation leads to a drastic reduction in  │
│  the wing's ability to generate lift. The **coefficient of lift** ($C_L$)   │
│  peaks at this point and then rapidly decreases.\n4.  **Consequences**:     │
│  With insufficient lift to counteract gravity, the aircraft will descend    │
│  rapidly, often with a nose-down pitch.\n\n**Why is it important for        │
│  flight safety?**\nUnderstanding and preventing stalls is fundamental to    │
│  flight safety. An aircraft that is not stalled will generally not enter a  │
│  spin, which is a much more complex and dangerous maneuver. Pilots are      │
│  trained extensively to recognize the early signs of a stall and to         │
│  recover from one safely by reducing the angle of attack and increasing     │
│  power.\n\n**Difficulty:** Medium",                                         │
